🎤 Interview Follow-up Questions & Answers

1. What is the PySpark equivalent of SQL CASE WHEN?

Answer:

when() and otherwise().

SQL:

CASE
    WHEN salary >= 70000 THEN 'A'
    WHEN salary >= 50000 THEN 'B'
    ELSE 'C'
END

PySpark:

when(col("salary") >= 70000, "A") \
.when(col("salary") >= 50000, "B") \
.otherwise("C")


---

2. Is otherwise() mandatory?

Answer:

No.

If you don't use otherwise(), rows that don't satisfy any when() condition will contain NULL.

Example:

when(col("salary") > 50000, "High")

Rows with salary ≤ 50000 will have NULL.


---

3. Can we chain multiple when() conditions?

Answer:

Yes.

Example:

when(condition1, value1) \
.when(condition2, value2) \
.when(condition3, value3) \
.otherwise(value4)

This is the standard approach for handling multiple conditions.


---

4. Can when() be used inside select()?

Answer:

Yes.

Example:

df.select(
    "name",
    when(col("salary") >= 50000, "Eligible")
    .otherwise("Not Eligible")
    .alias("status")
).show()

This is useful when you want to create a derived column without modifying the original DataFrame.


---

5. What happens if multiple when() conditions are true?

Answer:

Only the first matching condition is executed.

Evaluation stops after the first match, just like SQL CASE WHEN.

Example:

when(col("salary") >= 50000, "B")
.when(col("salary") >= 70000, "A")

A salary of 70000 will return "B", because the first condition is already satisfied.

Always write conditions from the most specific to the most general.


